e, England","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Frodesly, Shropshire, England":"Frodesley, Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","Sandbach, Cheshire, England":"Sandbach, Cheshire, England"},"en":{"1464–4 May 1543":"1464–4 May 1543","1464–1543":"1464–1543","1464–1538":"1464–1538","1466–1505":"1466–1505","1486–1538":"1486–1538","1444–1475":"1444–1475","1446–1480":"1446–1480","1495":"1495","1480":"1480","4 May 1543":"4 May 1543","1446":"1446","1444":"1444","1466":"1466","1543":"1543","1464":"1464","1475":"1475","1486":"1486","1485":"1485","1463":"1463","1505":"1505","14 February 1538":"14 February 1538","1538":"1538","Bradwell, Sandbach, Cheshire, England":"Sandbach, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Keele, Staffordshire, England":"Keele, Staffordshire, England","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Frodesly, Shropshire, England":"Frodesley, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Sandbach, Cheshire, England":"Sandbach, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Sneyd","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Sneyd in Burslem (Staffordshire), The Sneyd near Bloxwich (also Staffordshire), or Snead Farm and Snead Common in Rock (Worcestershire), all of which derived from Middle English <i>snede</i>, Old English <i>snǣd</i> ‘detached piece of land or woodland’. Compare   Snaith  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Snaith","meanings":["English: habitational name from Snaith in Yorkshire. The placename derives from Old Norse <i>sneith</i> ‘slice of land, piece of land cut off’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Sneyd was born in 1464, in Sandbach, Cheshire, England, his father, Nicholas Snede, was 20 and his mother, Lady Margaret Downes, was 18. He married Lady Susanna Ledsham in 1485, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 4 May 1543, in Keele, Staffordshire, England, at the age of 79."},"et":{"1464–4 May 1543":"1464–4. mai 1543","1464–1543":"1464–1543","1464–1538":"1464–1538","1466–1505":"1466–1505","1486–1538":"1486–1538","1444–1475":"1444–1475","1446–1480":"1446–1480","1495":"1495","1480":"1480","4 May 1543":"4. mai 1543","1446":"1446","1444":"1444","1466":"1466","1543":"1543","1464":"1464","1475":"1475","1486":"1486","1485":"1485","1463":"1463","1505":"1505","14 February 1538":"14. veebruar 1538","1538":"1538","Bradwell, Sandbach, Cheshire, England":"Sandbach, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Keele, Staffordshire, England":"Keele, Staffordshire, England","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Frodesly, Shropshire, England":"Frodesley, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Sandbach, Cheshire, England":"Sandbach, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"1464–4 May 1543":"1464–4. toukokuuta 1543","1464–1543":"1464–1543","1464–1538":"1464–1538","1466–1505":"1466–1505","1486–1538":"1486–1538","1444–1475":"1444–1475","1446–1480":"1446–1480","1495":"1495","1480":"1480","4 May 1543":"4. toukokuuta 1543","1446":"1446","1444":"1444","1466":"1466","1543":"1543","1464":"1464","1475":"1475","1486":"1486","1485":"1485","1463":"1463","1505":"1505","14 February 1538":"14. helmikuuta 1538","1538":"1538","Brad